OSI Model & TCP/IP Concepts – Daily Study Log


1. Source Address 

The IP address of the sending device.

Helps the data know where to return (reply path).



2. Destination Address

The IP address of the receiving device.

Helps the data know where to travel next.



3. Packets and Frames

Packets and frames are small pieces of data that form a large message.

Large messages are divided into small packets.

At the destination, packets are reconstructed into the original message.

Data exchange in small pieces reduces network bottlenecking.

Packets follow standard rules and protocols.

Standardization is important because billions of devices are connected to the Internet.



4. Encapsulation

This process is called encapsulation.

When talking about IP addresses, we are referring to packets.

When encapsulation information is stripped away, we are talking about the frame itself.

IP packets contain a header with additional information.



5. TCP/IP – Three-Way Handshake

Used to establish a connection between sender and receiver.

Ensures both sides are ready before data transmission begins.



6. Notable Headers


Time To Live (TTL)

Sets an expiry timer for packets.

Prevents packets from circulating endlessly in the network.


Checksum

Provides integrity checking (TCP/IP).

If data changes during transmission, the checksum value changes.

If checksum does not match, the packet is considered corrupt.
